'''Bassas da India''' is an uninhabited, roughly circular [[atoll]] that is part of the [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]]. Located in the southern [[Mozambique Channel]], about halfway between [[Mozambique]] and [[Madagascar]] (about {{convert|385|km|0|abbr=on}} further east) and around {{convert|110|km|0|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Europa Island]], the rim of the atoll averages around 100&nbsp;m in width and encloses a shallow [[lagoon]] of depth no greater than 15&nbsp;m. Overall, the atoll is about {{convert|10|km|0|abbr=on}} in diameter, rising steeply from the [[seabed]] 3000&nbsp;m below to encircle an area (including lagoon) of {{convert|80|km²|0|abbr=on}}. Its [[Exclusive Economic Zone]] (EEZ), {{convert|123700|km²|0|abbr=on}} in size, is [[Contiguity|contiguous]] with that of Europa Island.

The atoll consists of ten barren rocky islets, with no vegetation, totalling 0.2&nbsp;km² (.077 sq mi) in area. Those on the north and east sides are 2.1 to 3&nbsp;m high, while those on the west and south sides are 1.2&nbsp;m high. The reef, whose coastline measures {{convert|35.2|km|0|abbr=on}}, is completely covered by the sea from three hours before [[Tide|high tide]] to three hours afterward. The region is also subject to [[cyclone]]s, making the atoll a long-time maritime hazard and the site of numerous shipwrecks.

[[Jaguar Seamount]] and [[Hall Tablemount]] lie, respectively, about 40 and 70&nbsp;km further southwest.

