== History ==

The Bassas da India was first recorded by [[Portuguese explorers]] in the early sixteenth century as the "'''''Baixo da'' Judia'''" ("''Jewess'' Shoals"). The ''Judia'' ("''Jewess''", for the ancestry of its owner [[Fernão de Loronha]]<ref>Bernardo Gomes de Brito. ''Historia Tragico-Maritima. Em que se escrevem chronologicamente os Naufragios que tiverão as Naos de Portugal, depois que se poz em exercicio a Navegação da India.'' Lisboa 1735</ref>) was the Portuguese ship that discovered the feature by running aground on it in 1506.<ref>Natal Museum. ''Natal Museum journal of humanities'', Vol. 12. The Museum Council (Pietermaritzburg), 2000.</ref> The name became "'''Bassas da India'''" due to transcription errors by cartographers. The ''Santiago'' broke up on the shoal in 1585.

It was rediscovered by the ''Europa'' in 1774, whence the name "Europa Rocks".<ref>"...Europa [R]ocks, was {{sic}} discovered by the ship ''Europa'' in 1774." In ''Africa pilot, Part 3'' Hydrographic Office of Great Britain.</ref> The ''Malay'' was lost 27 July 1842 on the Europa Rocks.<ref>Historical Sketch of Salem, 1626-1879.</ref>

In 1897, the shoal became a [[Third French Republic|French]] possession, later being placed under the administration of a commissioner residing in [[Réunion]] in 1968. [[Madagascar]] continues to claim sovereignty over the islands.

== Tourism ==

[[Mooring (watercraft)|Mooring]] at Bassas da India requires a permit from the French Government.<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.taaf.fr/Acces-aux-iles-Eparses Iles Eparses Access]</ref> Fishing without such a permit may result in the boat being expelled or even confiscated.<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do;jsessionid=9453DD60B82493F7FCE3C5E284809744.tpdjo15v_1?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000880593&dateTexte=19960708 5 July 1983 French Law]</ref>

